<BaseLayout title="US immigration and crime: what official federal data shows | Immigration Factbook" lang="en" altHref="/faq/us-immigration-crime-statistics/" description="The United States does not publish systematic federal crime statistics disaggregated by immigration status. What data exists, and what it cannot establish.">
<main class="theme-page">
  <div class="theme-hero">
    <nav class="breadcrumb"><a href="/en/">Immigration Factbook</a> › <span>FAQ</span></nav>
    <div class="theme-hero__badge">BJS · FBI UCR/NIBRS · ICE/DHS — US Federal Official Data</div>
    <h1>US Immigration &amp; Crime<br>What Official Federal Data Shows<em>No systematic cross-tabulation exists</em></h1>
    <p class="theme-hero__sub">Unlike Sweden, Denmark, or Norway, the US does not publish systematic federal crime statistics disaggregated by immigration status. This page explains what data exists and what it cannot establish.</p>
    <div class="theme-hero__meta">
      <span class="lang-pill"><a href="/faq/us-immigration-crime-statistics/">🌐 日本語</a></span>
      <span class="meta-note">Primary official sources only</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section>
    <h2>What federal data exists</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Data source</th>
          <th>What it covers</th>
          <th>What it does not cover</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><a href="https://www.bjs.gov" rel="noopener">Bureau of Justice Statistics (BJS)</a></td>
          <td>Incarceration rates by race/ethnicity; victimisation surveys (NCVS)</td>
          <td>No systematic disaggregation by nativity or immigration status</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><a href="https://www.fbi.gov/services/cjis/ucr" rel="noopener">FBI Uniform Crime Reporting (UCR) / NIBRS</a></td>
          <td>Arrest and offence data by age, sex, race</td>
          <td>No immigration status variable collected</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><a href="https://www.ice.gov" rel="noopener">ICE / DHS</a></td>
          <td>Deportation and enforcement data; criminal alien removals</td>
          <td>Not comparable to general population crime rates; reflects enforcement priorities, not crime incidence</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>State-level data (varies by state)</td>
          <td>Some states publish incarceration by citizenship (e.g., Texas DPS)</td>
          <td>Not nationally representative; coverage and methodology vary</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why no systematic federal cross-tabulation exists</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Immigration status is not collected as a variable in the FBI's UCR/NIBRS arrest database.</li>
      <li>The Census Bureau's American Community Survey (ACS) collects nativity and citizenship but is not linked to criminal justice administrative data at the federal level.</li>
      <li>The Department of Justice does not publish a routine report comparing crime rates of native-born vs. foreign-born or documented vs. undocumented populations.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What academic and state-level studies show</h2>
    <p>In the absence of federal cross-tabulations, academic researchers have used linked administrative datasets or state-level sources. Peer-reviewed studies (e.g., Chalfin 2014, Butcher &amp; Piehl 2007, Adelman et al. 2017) consistently find that immigrants — including undocumented immigrants — are incarcerated at lower rates than native-born Americans. However, these are not official federal statistics and reflect specific methodological choices.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Texas DPS data: the most cited state-level official dataset. Shows lower conviction rates for both legal and undocumented immigrants than native-born Texans. Caveat: Texas is not representative of national patterns.</li>
      <li>ICE enforcement data is sometimes cited, but records deportees with criminal convictions — a self-selected group, not a representative crime rate for the immigrant population.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What this means for comparisons</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>The United States cannot be compared on this metric to Sweden (BRÅ), Denmark (DST), or Norway (SSB), which publish national per-capita suspect or conviction rates by immigrant background.</li>
      <li>Claims that the US has a higher or lower immigrant crime rate than European countries lack the data to support them.</li>
      <li>Immigration Factbook marks the US crime-by-immigration-status cell as "no systematic federal cross-tabulation" rather than presenting a figure that does not exist in that form.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Primary references</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Bureau of Justice Statistics. <em>National Crime Victimization Survey (NCVS)</em>. <a href="https://www.bjs.gov" rel="noopener">bjs.gov</a></li>
      <li>FBI. <em>Crime in the United States / NIBRS</em>. <a href="https://www.fbi.gov/services/cjis/ucr" rel="noopener">fbi.gov</a></li>
      <li>Texas Department of Public Safety. <em>Conviction and Arrest Rates of Undocumented Immigrants</em> (annual). <a href="https://www.dps.texas.gov" rel="noopener">dps.texas.gov</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

